content_chunks.content: This digital course is designed to provide knowledge and practical experience in 3 levels (basic, intermediate, and advanced) on soil testing of building foundations as precisely as possible. Geotechnical investigations provide essential information about the soil's physical and mechanical properties, such as compressibility, shear strength and bearing capacity. Accurate characterization of these properties helps in: selecting appropriate foundation types; determining the load-bearing capacity of the ground; designing foundations that minimize settlement and prevent failure. Poor understanding of soil conditions can lead to foundation failure, resulting in severe structural issues such as cracking, tilting, or collapse. This course would enable to achieve the economy of materials and labour expenditures for the construction of foundations. In this course, students'll learn how to test soil accurately, analyze the results, and apply this data to make informed engineering decisions.

Geotechnical laboratory testing technology for accurate soil characterization and foundation engineering - this course delivers comprehensive expertise in performing precise soil testing procedures that determine critical physical and mechanical properties for building foundation design. Students master soil mechanics fundamentals, granulometric analysis, moisture content testing, permeability evaluation, and Atterberg limits determination that inform optimal foundation selection. The curriculum covers Proctor compaction testing, shear strength analysis, compressibility assessment, and consolidation evaluation methods that prevent foundation failures and optimize structural performance. Graduates emerge skilled in implementing geotechnical testing protocols, analyzing soil behavior patterns, and applying engineering data to design foundations that minimize settlement, maximize load-bearing capacity, and achieve economical material and labor usage in construction projects.
